=========================================
DEQUE INTERNAL WORKING
=========================================

Interview Answer:

A deque is implemented using multiple fixed-size memory blocks and a map
(array of pointers) that points to those blocks. Unlike vector, which uses
one contiguous memory block, deque stores elements across several blocks,
allowing efficient insertion and deletion at both ends.

-----------------------------------------
1. Vector Internal Structure
-----------------------------------------

Vector uses ONE contiguous memory block.

Memory:

[10][20][30][40][50]

Advantages:
✓ Fast random access
✓ Excellent cache locality

Problem:
✗ Front insertion requires shifting all elements

Example:

Insert 5 at front

Before:

[10][20][30][40][50]

After:

[5][10][20][30][40][50]

All elements moved.

Cost = O(n)

-----------------------------------------
2. Deque Internal Structure
-----------------------------------------

Deque uses:

1. Map (array of pointers)
2. Multiple fixed-size memory blocks

Structure:

Map
+-----+-----+-----+
| B1  | B2  | B3  |
+-----+-----+-----+

B1 -> [10][20][30]
B2 -> [40][50][60]
B3 -> [70][80][90]

Logical View:

10 20 30 40 50 60 70 80 90

Physical View:

Block1 somewhere in memory
Block2 somewhere else
Block3 somewhere else

Not contiguous.

-----------------------------------------
3. How push_front() Works
-----------------------------------------

Current:

B1 -> [10][20][30]

push_front(5)

Instead of shifting elements,
deque places the new element in available space.

Result:

B1 -> [5][10][20][30]

No shifting.

Complexity:

O(1)

-----------------------------------------
4. What If Front Block Is Full?
-----------------------------------------

Current:

B1 -> [10][20][30]

push_front(5)

No space available.

Deque allocates a NEW block.

Map

+-----+-----+-----+-----+
| NB  | B1  | B2  | B3  |
+-----+-----+-----+-----+

NB -> [5]
B1 -> [10][20][30]

Existing elements are NOT moved.

Still O(1).

-----------------------------------------
5. How push_back() Works
-----------------------------------------

Current:

B3 -> [70][80]

push_back(90)

Result:

B3 -> [70][80][90]

No shifting.

Complexity:

O(1)

If block becomes full:

Allocate a new block at the end.

-----------------------------------------
6. How Random Access Works
-----------------------------------------

Suppose:

Block Size = 3

B1 -> [10][20][30]
B2 -> [40][50][60]
B3 -> [70][80][90]

Want:

d[4]

Calculation:

block = 4 / 3 = 1
offset = 4 % 3 = 1

Access:

B2[1] = 50

Complexity:

O(1)

-----------------------------------------
7. Why Is Deque Not Contiguous?
-----------------------------------------

Because elements are spread across multiple blocks.

Example:

B1 -> Memory Location 1000
B2 -> Memory Location 5000
B3 -> Memory Location 9000

Blocks are separate.

Unlike vector:

[10][20][30][40][50]

which occupies one continuous memory region.

-----------------------------------------
8. Why Use Deque?
-----------------------------------------

Advantages:

✓ O(1) push_front()
✓ O(1) push_back()
✓ O(1) pop_front()
✓ O(1) pop_back()
✓ O(1) random access

Disadvantages:

✗ Not contiguous memory
✗ Slightly worse cache locality than vector

