DEQUE INTERVIEW QUESTIONS & ANSWERS
=========================================

1. What is deque?
-----------------

deque (Double Ended Queue) is an STL sequence container that allows efficient insertion and deletion of elements at both the front and the back while still providing O(1) random access.

-----------------------------------------

2. Why is it called double-ended queue?
----------------------------------------

Because elements can be inserted and removed efficiently from both ends:

Front:
push_front()
pop_front()

Back:
push_back()
pop_back()

Unlike a queue, which allows insertion at one end and deletion at the other, deque supports operations at both ends.

-----------------------------------------

3. How is deque implemented internally?
-----------------------------------------

A deque is implemented using multiple fixed-size memory blocks and a map (array of pointers) that points to those blocks.

Visual:

Map
 |
 +--> Block1
 +--> Block2
 +--> Block3

Benefits:
- Fast insertion at front
- Fast insertion at back
- O(1) random access

Since new blocks can be added at either end, deque avoids the expensive shifting required by vector.

-----------------------------------------

4. Difference between vector and deque?
-----------------------------------------

vector
------
- Contiguous memory
- O(1) push_back()
- O(n) push_front()
- Better cache locality
- Faster traversal

deque
-----
- Non-contiguous memory
- O(1) push_back()
- O(1) push_front()
- Slightly worse cache locality
- Efficient operations at both ends

Interview Answer:
Use vector when most insertions are at the back and cache performance matters. Use deque when insertions/removals are frequent at both ends.

-----------------------------------------

5. Does deque store elements contiguously?
------------------------------------------

No.

Unlike vector, deque stores elements in multiple memory blocks.

Therefore:

vector:
✓ Contiguous memory

deque:
✗ Non-contiguous memory

-----------------------------------------

6. Does deque support random access?
------------------------------------

Yes.

Example:

deque<int> d;
cout << d[5];

Complexity:

O(1)

Although memory is not contiguous, deque can directly calculate the block and offset of an element, allowing constant-time access.

-----------------------------------------

7. Complexity of push_front()?
------------------------------

O(1)

Reason:
Deque can add elements at the front without shifting existing elements.

Example:

d.push_front(10);

-----------------------------------------

8. Complexity of push_back()?
-----------------------------

O(1)

Reason:
Elements are added at the end without shifting existing elements.

Example:

d.push_back(20);

-----------------------------------------

9. Why is front insertion faster than vector?
---------------------------------------------

Vector stores elements in a single contiguous memory block.

Example:

[10][20][30]

Insert at front:

[5][10][20][30]

All existing elements must be shifted.

Complexity:

O(n)

Deque stores elements in multiple blocks.

It can allocate space at the front without shifting all elements.

Complexity:

O(1)

-----------------------------------------

10. When would you choose deque over vector?
--------------------------------------------

Choose deque when:

✓ Frequent push_front()
✓ Frequent pop_front()
✓ Frequent push_back()
✓ Frequent pop_back()

Example:
- Sliding Window problems
- Implementing queues
- Task scheduling systems

Choose vector when:

✓ Mostly push_back()
✓ Better cache locality required
✓ Need contiguous memory
✓ Interfacing with C APIs

